Now `ngx_accept_disabled` and load balancing. From `ngx_event_accept.c:139`:
```c
ngx_accept_disabled = ngx_cycle->connection_n / 8
                      - ngx_cycle->free_connection_n;
```
So after each accept, `ngx_accept_disabled = connection_n/8 - free_connection_n`. When free connections are plentiful (free > connection_n/8), this is negative, meaning the worker is "willing" to accept more. When free connections drop below connection_n/8 (i.e., this worker is getting full), `ngx_accept_disabled` becomes positive.

Back in `ngx_process_events_and_timers`:
```c
if (ngx_accept_disabled > 0) {
    ngx_accept_disabled--;
}
```
When positive, the worker does NOT try to grab the accept lock (it decrements the counter instead, gradually coming back). This naturally biases connection acceptance toward workers with more free connections — a simple but effective load balancer.

