void
ngx_event_expire_timers(void)
{
    ...
    for ( ;; ) {
        root = ngx_event_timer_rbtree.root;
        if (root == sentinel) return;
        node = ngx_rbtree_min(root, sentinel);
        if ((ngx_msec_int_t)(node->key - ngx_current_msec) > 0) return;  // not expired yet
        ev = ngx_rbtree_data(node, ngx_event_t, timer);
        ngx_rbtree_delete(&ngx_event_timer_rbtree, &ev->timer);
        ev->timer_set = 0;
        ev->timedout = 1;
        ev->handler(ev);  // fire the timer
    }
}
```
Loops over the rbtree (min first), firing all timers whose key <= current_msec. Sets `ev->timedout = 1` so the handler can distinguish a timeout from a normal I/O ready event.

`ngx_event_find_timer`:
```c
ngx_msec_t
ngx_event_find_timer(void)
{
    ...
    if (root == sentinel) return NGX_TIMER_INFINITE;
    node = ngx_rbtree_min(root, sentinel);
    timer = (ngx_msec_int_t)(node->key - ngx_current_msec);
    return (ngx_msec_t)(timer > 0 ? timer : 0);
}
```
Returns the time until the earliest timer expires (0 if already past), or INFINITE if no timers. This becomes the epoll_wait timeout.

